<h1><i>If only it were so easy to stop the tics!</h1>
<img src="/images/tourettes-writing-tic.png" style="float:left;padding:0 10px 15px 0;width:70px;" alt="Involuntary tics can manifest in writing and drawing." title="Involuntary tics can manifest in writing and drawing."/><p>For people with Tourette Syndrome, involuntary tics are quite common. They often manifest themselves in peculiar muscle spasms and releases of energy. Yet this neurological disorder often exhibits other symptoms as well.</p>
<div style="clear:both;"></div>
<ul><li><h2>What exactly is Tourettes?</h2></li></ul>

<p >Tourettes, also known as Gilles de la Tourette syndrome (or TS for short), is a severe neurological disorder characterized by multiple facial and other body tics. It usually begins in childhood or adolescence and often is accompanied by grunts and compulsive utterances, as of interjections and obscenities. Besides tics, people with TS may also exhibit Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder (OCD).</p>

<ul><li><h2>Why is Band of Artists spreading awareness about TS?</h2></li></ul>

<img src="/images/tourettes-inspired-performance.jpg" style="float:right;padding:0 0 10px 15px;width:200px;" alt="Inspired by her own case of Tourette Syndrome, Sutie Madison directed and produced Intersection in 2011." title="Inspired by her own case of Tourette Syndrome, Sutie Madison directed and produced Intersection in 2011."/>
<p >Founder and Director Sutie Madison has Tourette Syndrome and is taking her neurological disorder to a new level. Using physical and vocal tics as a foundation for choreography and the "formula" to her creative process, Sutie collaborates with several artists, neurologists, and performers to produce a variety of projects.  According to Sutie:</p>

<blockquote >"Band of Artists both ignites imagination and inspires tolerance and understanding for people who are different. I hope that you will take the time to learn about our organization and spread awareness for our cause, to help make a difference for the many lives impacted by neurological disorders such as Tourette Syndrome."</blockquote>

